A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Nuclear Command, Control, and Communications (NC3) Advanced Concepts are required for analysis, development and prototyping of next generation NC3 systems
and subsystems. This program ensures a responsive design and development engineering infrastructure to address evolving Nuclear Deterrence Operations (NDO)
mission requirements; emerging issues and technology insertion/technology application on the NC3 Weapon System (WS), future strategic systems/capability, and other
common strategic areas where appropriate; and develop enhanced multi-use capabilities. The NC3 Advanced Concepts Program will provide technology maturation and
risk reduction activities to support the AF NC3 Weapon System (AN/USQ-225). Activity will reduce life cycle costs, inform technology maturation & risk reduction efforts,
improve system performance, mitigate evolving threats, and ensure both viability and durability of the AF NC3 Weapon System.

"NC3 Prototypes & Demonstrations” will focus on the development and operational evaluation of emerging capabilities. This area will 1) create functional prototypes
of technologies and system concepts to assess their utility and technical feasibility, 2) conduct a series of demonstrations and experiments in operationally relevant
environments to validate performance, and 3) leverage comprehensive methodology to respond to changing warfighter needs to inform requirement refinement. The
objective is to reduce technical risk, accelerate the learning process, and provide tangible evidence to guide formal acquisition and integration decisions.

"NC3 Technology Insertion & Transition” will bridge the gap between mature prototypes and their integration into operational programs of record. Key activities include
1) identifying and maturing promising technologies from prototypes, laboratory environments, and industry, 2) developing transition plans and strategies in collaboration
with NC3 programs or other stakeholders to ensure successful handoffs, and 3) providing advice on the integration of these new capabilities into the existing NC3
architecture and sustainment planning. This ensures that successful innovations are effectively scaled and delivered to programs, reducing life cycle costs, and providing
mature technologies.



Additional details can be provided at a higher classification.

Program RDT&E funding may be utilized to implement innovation insertion, capability insertion, software increments, spiral upgrades, modular component swaps, and
other insertions consistent with Modular Open System Architecture. Program RDT&E funding may be utilized to design, develop, integrate, and test weapon system
and/or component level open architectures. Program RDT&E funding may be utilized to fund the concept refinement, design, development, integration, and testing of
interdependent technologies and common architectures that underpin weapon system and portfolio-wide mission outcomes.


